34th Street, west from 237 West 34th, north side, west of Seventh Avenue.
Between the West Side Bank (later taken over by the Manufacturers' Trust Company), on the N.W. corner of Eighth Avenue, and the Manhattan Opera House, may be seen the tower of the abandoned Thirty-Fourth Street [Dutch] Reformed Church. Around 1927 this and the bank building will be demolished for the site of the Hotel New Yorker.

1920.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

441-447 Seventh Ave., at, adjoining and north of the N.E. corner of 34th Street.
About 1922.
Gift of E. M. Jenks.

A general view of the midtown Manhattan area containing the dominant Pennsylvania Railroad Station. To the right and left of same, on Seventh and Eighth Avenues respectively are the Pennsylvania Hotel and the Equitable Building, and the U.S.P.O. 's General Station. 34th Street runs diagonally across the center, while 42nd Street is across the top. On the former (left) is the unfinished Hotel New Yorker. Immediately beyond is the famous Garment Center of the City.


1929

title: 167 West 34th Street (Broadway - Seventh Avenue)

text:
441 to 461 Seventh Ave., east side, north from West 34th (right) to 35th (left) Streets, showing a 16-story structure under demolition. Upon this site and in conjunction with the 4-story corner structure shown, R. H. Macy and Co., erected a 19-story building, there by occupying the entire block with the exclusion of two small corners; one of which would be on the left. Other buildings of this huge retail enterprise appear on the right; they, forming the north side of West 34th Street, from Seventh Ave., to Broadway. This set consists of a negative and a positive.

May 22, 1930.

F. M. Demarest.
Gift of Albert A. Volk Co.
